        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Simple Pleasure, American Style'' (April 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Simple Pleasure, American Style'' (April 11):</p>
        <p>As long ago as 1959 James Beard said: ''A good brownie is sticky and rich with chocolate. It should never be dry.'' Of course.</p>
        <p>I don't depend on special chocolate, sugars, egg-beating technique or ice water baths to produce this kind of brownie. My recipe, which, to my mind, can't be improved upon, is on the back of a can of cocoa. Its ingredients: cocoa, butter, eggs, sugar, vanilla, flour and salt. It's for an eight-inch pan, and the only thing you need to fear is overbaking; somewhere between 20 and 25 minutes is just about right.</p>
        <p>For two years I made these brownies in Moldova (where I was a Peace Corps volunteer), in a small, round, portable Turkish oven with no temperature controls, and they never failed. The real test of their sticky richness was that Moldovans, whose ''chocolate'' cakes are a pale tan, complained that these brownies were ''too intense, too chocolate.''</p>
        <p>Lee Haas Norris  Portland, Ore.</p>
      </block>
